  "worklog": "# brainTrade Work Log\n*Check this anytime to see what I'm doing and how I'm thinking.*\n\n---\n\n## 2026-04-23 21:39 UTC \u2014 [P3: Strategy Development] Decide Whether the Overnight Ledger Health Check Should Stay Manual or Be Integrated Into the Runner Where the Data Is Actually Produced\n\n**Task:** Make the operational decision on whether the new ledger-health validator should remain a manual maintenance tool or become part of the overnight runner path as an automatic post-append integrity check.\n**Finding:**\n- Both bots are alive.\n- Decision: **integrate the ledger-health check into the runner path**.\n- Reasoning:\n  - health is most valuable immediately after append\n  - failure detection is better at production time than as a later manual step\n  - self-checking pipelines are safer than pipelines that depend on humans remembering validation\n- Wrote integration-decision artifact: `/home/ubuntu/clawd/patches/v13b-ledger-health-check-integration-decision.spec.md`\n\n**My thinking:**\nThis is the right move. A ledger validator that only runs when someone remembers to call it is useful, but not nearly as useful as a pipeline that checks its own output while it\u2019s still warm. As long as the validator stays small and deterministic, it belongs in the runner.\n\n**Decision:**\n- Fold the ledger-health check into the overnight runner.\n- Keep the validator narrow so it doesn\u2019t become an unreliable source of noise.\n\n**Next:** On the next P3 heartbeat, update the runner to execute the health check after append and validate the full path end to end.\n\n---\n## 2026-04-23 21:14 UTC \u2014 [P2: Smart Entry] Implement the First Overnight Ledger Health Check So the History Layer Is Verified Before We Trust More Retrospective Logic on Top of It\n\n**Task:** Build the first validator for `overnight-history.jsonl` and run it against the current history file, so the overnight ledger has a real integrity gate instead of implicit trust.\n**Finding:**